y redacted ones, this becomes copy-on-redact without changing policy.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\\\" start=8 end=10 priority=3 confidence=0.78}\\n\\n::code-comment{title=\\\"[P3] Key matching allocates per object key\\\" body=\\\"`to_ascii_lowercase().replace(...)` creates normalized strings for every object key while walking each source record. An allocation-free normalized comparison/normalized suffix check would remove that churn without changing the sensitive-key policy.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\\\" start=45 end=47 priority=3 confidence=0.86}\\n\\n::code-comment{title=\\\"[P3] Count assertions duplicate privacy checks\\\" body=\\\"Several tests assert exact redaction counts after already asserting the redacted fields or values. Unless count granularity is the behavior under test, this couples tests to traversal/tokenization details. Keeping one focused count test and letting the rest assert privacy outcomes would make policy-neutral simplifications easier.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\\\" start=236 priority=3 confidence=0.7}\\n\\nI did not find obvious quadratic behavior in the token scan; candidate slicing, UUID windows, entropy, and timestamp checks are all linear per candidate. I also did not edit files or run tests.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>"}]}}}